metadata.name: September #271
metadata.description:
The Summer Ends
---------------
Controls:
S or double tap (mobile): Download image

A: Toggle loading animation (off by default to improve performance)

1-6: Modify scale (1 = default, 1500 x 2000px, 6 = maximum, 9000 x 12000px (performance intensive, will take a long time to render))
F: Fit to current screen size

T: Toggle grain and texture overlay
H: Toggle shape outlines

B: Cycle border sizes (0 -> 50 -> 75 -> 100 -> 150px)
C: Cycle border colors

I: Cycle visible layers

L: Toggle “live mode”. This mode will continuously redraw a new output every few seconds using the same base parameters as the original output, but with slight variations.

You can modify the x and y url parameters to set a custom size. Note that the image will change to fit the new size, but overall drawing style, colors, etc. will remain the same.
(For example, for a 1000x2000 image, add &x=1000&y=2000)

metadata.name: Isola della Scala #68
metadata.description:
All things pass, all things flow,
Movement, connection, separation, all in tow.
A misstep and we're knocked off course,
But in the end, we rise, as if by force.
Like a dance of dominoes, we fall and we stand,
In this ever-changing world, we're a part of the grand.

The name of this work is the name of the city where my roots began, where the path of everything changed and new directions in life were taken.

Made with p5.js, p5.grain and much love

metadata.name: Shattered Obelisks #75
metadata.description:
Shattered Obelisks began as a work that is dedicated to my habit of mindlessly drawing on paper when I am stressed, depressed or immersed in difficult thoughts.

Like a patient undergoing psychotherapy and piecing together the causes of unconscious fears and anxieties, I and my artwork have assembled ourselves into something shaped, found order in the chaos and separated it from the external noise.

It took 3 months of continuous, obsessive work. I have developed a huge library, designed for hand-like drawing. The functionality of this library is four times larger than what is shown in this drop.

I plan to put this library out into the public domain when I deem it complete, and hope that it will help someone express themselves through the creative process as much as it helped for me.

In case you've encountered a problem with inverted colours, try changing browser or disabling extensions. This problem only occurred once during testing on a massive amount of devices and was resolved by disabling extensions.

IMPORTANT NOTES BLOCK:

NOTE 1: This artwork should be viewed at a browser scale of 100%. Reducing the scale will increase the amount of detail, but may unpredictably affect the preservation of the location of secondary objects.

NOTE 2: This work can be printed on a plotter. Click S for saving it in .SVG.
Detailed instructions and answers to possible questions can be found in the console output of the code.

NOTE 3: This drop is the first one from the series of 3. It will be used as AL ticket in next drops of this series.

metadata.name: FX(T)RASH #419
metadata.description:
Imagine having Van Gogh's ear in a little box, getting your grubby hands on Banksy's stencils or Zancan's plotter! Well, here's something just as awesome - This is your chance to collect some trash straight from the King of Trash Art himself, Robness!

---

NOR44 & ROBNESS V2 JOIN FORCES TO CREATE A SPECIAL GENERATIVE PROJECT IN HONOR OF THE SECOND #TEZTRASH EVENT ON 12/21/22.  TEZTRASH IS A TEZOS COMMUNITY DAY WHEN THE CRYPTONATIVE ART MOVEMENT #TRASHART AND TRASH ART IN GENERAL IS CELEBRATED.  THE PREVIOUS TEZTRASH EVENT WAS A MONUMENTAL HIT ON TWITTER AND THIS TIME AROUND WE'VE DECIDED TO CONCOCT AN EPIC GENERATIVE DROP WHILST KEEPING THE TRASH ART ETHOS EMBEDDED IN THE WORK. HERE WE PLAY WITH THE NOTION OF 'TRASHING JPEGS' AND REINSERTING A PHYSICAL YET GENERATIVE REPRESENTATION OF THAT IDEA. ENJOY AND HAPPY TEZTRASH 2.0 DAY!

---

This generative artwork is composed of many layers of pre-rendered images with code utilized to stylize as well as randomly position, rotate and scale these elements, creating potentially infinite unique compositions resembling real-world outputs from a Photocopier/Copy Machine that's seen better days.

metadata.name: Ridge Scribbles #61
metadata.description:
Ridge scribbles is the first piece of a small series around mountain landscapes using different rendering techniques.

A heightmap is generated using fractal noise with different parameters and scales. Then we generate tens of thousands of paths by using a gradient descent algorithm with momentum, starting at random positions on the reversed heightmap. Those paths are then rendered using one of 11 different colour palettes.

Press "s" to save a screenshot.

Original artwork by William Watkins · Lyon, 2022
